<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="7dad70b5-9c0d-53ac-a233-fdbec9ee5d17" activityNameId="3442a037-1bab-47d6-a54d-723aa805805b" parentActivityId="40aedb07-48aa-46ce-8064-405ca6fc678c" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">light olefins production, from methanol-to-olefins conversion, ethylene-to-propylene ratio of 0.67</activityName>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts with the raw materials entering the methano-to-olefins facility.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">The activity ends with the final products being ready for further processing or transportation at the production site gate. The dataset includes the consumption of raw materials and energy, estimated catalyst use, emissions to air and water from the process, as well as the infrastructure use. </includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the combined production of light olefins via the catalytic dehydration of methanol. Namely, this dataset covers the production of 1.00 kg of propylene and 0.67 kg of ethylene as reference products. At the same time, the formed liquefied petroleum gas, pentane, and gasoline (0.03, 0.04, and 0.06 kg, respectively) are treated as valuable by-products. The process includes, feedstock, materials, energy and registers all relevant direct emissions.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Light olefins are crucial building blocks for the chemicals and plastics sector and are predominantly generated through steam cracking of hydrocarbons. The annual production volume of ethylene and propylene are extremely high and constitutes them as the most highly produced petrochemicals. The high production volume of light olefins is driven by a high demand, which in 2007 amounted to 115 and 73 Mt for ethylene and propylene, respectively.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Notably, methanol may be used to cover part of the ethylene and propylene demand. Besides, such pathway may be appealing to decouple the production of light olefins from the petroleum feedstocks, e.g., naphtha.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">The share of the produced light olefins, through the methanol-to-olefins (MTO) process, depends on the operating conditions of the reactor and the used catalyst. The latter process variables are able to modify the weight ratio of propylene-to-ethylene, to either maximize the yield towards ethylene or propylene (i.e., amount of ethylene &lt; propylene, or vice versa). Furthermore, the upgrade of C4-C5 fractions is also considered, enhancing the yield towards propylene.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">In the present dataset, there are two reference products (ethylene and propylene), thus allocation (subdivision) of the Life Cycle Inventory (LCI) is required. The allocation is based on mass content. For more information, consult the ''Modelling &amp; Administrative'' section.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Olah, G.A. (2005), Beyond Oil and Gas: The Methanol Economy. Angewandte Chemie International Edition, 44: 2636-2639. https://doi.org/10.1002/anie.200462121</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Yang, M., Fan, D., Wei, Y., Tian, P., Liu, Z., Recent Progress in Methanol-to-Olefins (MTO) Catalysts. Adv. Mater. 2019, 31, 1902181. https://doi.org/10.1002/adma.201902181</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Bertau, M., Offermanns, H., Plass, L., Schmidt, F., &amp; Wernicke, H. J. (Eds.). (2014). Methanol: the basic chemical and energy feedstock of the future (Vol. 1). Heidelberg: Springer.</text>
        </generalComment>
        <tag>combined production</tag>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0c40fa1e-7d7e-11de-9ae2-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">CN</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This inventory is modelled for China, where the coal-to- and methanol-to-olefins technologies are important technological pathways to produce light olefins.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">According to Lv et al (2021), in 2019, 24% of propylene produced in China was supplied from methanol conversion plants. Furthermore, based on Wood Mackenzie, in 2019, the installed capacity of ethylene from CTO/MTO accounted for 21% of China’s total ethylene capacity.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">This activity originates from literature data for the conversion of methanol to olefins (MTO) for China. The material and energy inputs reflect well the production technology and are, therefore, considered to be valid for the chosen geography.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">2021, Lin Lv, Guobao Song, Xinyue Zhao, Jingwen Chen, Environmental Burdens of China’s Propylene manufacturing: Comparative life-cycle assessment and scenario analysis, Science of the Total Environment, 799</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">https://www.woodmac.com/news/can-chinas-cto-and-mto-industries-survive-the-threat-of-massive-steam-cracker-investment/, assessed in 2023-10-09.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">In this dataset, the catalytic conversion of methanol to light olefins originates from  the work by Lv et al. (2021) that was, in turn, based on the environmental impact assessment report for a joint venture between China Power Investment Corporation and Total, Ltd., in Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, China.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">In the methanol-to-olefins process, the methanol feedstock is first dehydrated to dimethyl ether (DME), and DME, in turn, dehydrates further to yield ethylene, propylene, and smaller amounts of butenes. Hence, the conversion of methanol into olefins covers the following reaction steps:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">1) Dehydration of methanol to DME: </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">2 CH3OH &lt;--&gt; CH3OCH3 + H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">2) Production of light olefins through DME dehydration:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">CH3OCH3 --&gt; C2H4 + H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">CH3OCH3 --&gt; 2/3 C3H6 + H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">CH3OCH3 --&gt; 2/4 C4H8 + H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Other reactions take place simultaneously, which give yield to methane, ethane, C5 hydrocarbons, hydrogen, coke, and CO2. At the same time, additional steps to upgrade the C4-C5 fractions could enhance the yield towards propylene.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">This inventory covers the production of propylene, ethylene, LPG, C5s, and gasoline, along with the consumption of energy and auxiliary materials and services. The data is based on an existing project for the coal-to-olefins production process. Namely, the plant, which this inventory represents, is located in the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region of China and was built in 2016. This plant has an annual olefin output of 800 000 t,</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11">2021, Lin Lv, Guobao Song, Xinyue Zhao, Jingwen Chen, Environmental Burdens of China’s Propylene manufacturing: Comparative life-cycle assessment and scenario analysis, Science of the Total Environment, 799</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="12">Bertau, M., Offermanns, H., Plass, L., Schmidt, F., &amp; Wernicke, H. J. (Eds.). (2014). Methanol: the basic chemical and energy feedstock of the future (Vol. 1). Heidelberg: Springer.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2021-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This activity originates from literature data, for conversion of methanol to olefins (MTO) published in 2021. The material and energy inputs reflect well the production technology and not expected to change significantly over the next 5 years.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Lv, L.; Song, G.; Zhao, X.; Chen, J. (2021): Environmental Burdens of China’s Propylene manufacturing: Comparative life-cycle assessment and scenario analysis, Science of the Total Environment, 799, 149451.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
